commitResults.messageTitle: Update DG - user stories, use cases, NFRs, glossary
Update find command to accept Predicate<Person>
commitResults.messageBody:
The find command originally was written to search a person by name.
However, with the new decision to accept 'name' as a common attribute
and 'phone' and 'email' as unique identifiers, and potentially more
unique identifiers in the future, the find command should not only
accept a predicate that matches a person's name, but other attributes
too. Or even, a predicate that can match multiple attributes at the same
time!

Let's loosen the FindCommand class to accept a general Predicate related
to a Person. In this iteration, only phone number and email are checked,
so two classes EmailIsKeywordPredicate and PhoneIsKeywordPredicate are
implemented, which exactly matches a person's email address and phone
number respectively.

Let's also add unit test cases for the new predicates and update the
test cases for the FindCommand class.

commitResults.messageTitle: Rework delete command and add tests
commitResults.messageBody:
The 'delete' command inly supported delete by index. This is not an
ideal behaviour when the user already knows the exact person to delete,
as he/she will have to first find/filter to get to the person, and
delete the corresponding index.

Let's overload the 'delete' command to now support deletion by index and
unique identifiers (until v1.3, unique identifiers are phone number and
email address). Deletion by unique identifiers follow the pre-existing
prefix framework to make the user experience consistent. Also, unlike
deletion by index that depends on the currently filtered list displayed
to the user, deletion by unique identifiers will work regardless of what
is displayed.

commitResults.messageTitle: Refine ImportCommand for append and ignore dupes

commitResults.messageBody:
The import command only supported overwrite. This is undesirable
behaviour because a user may have multiple JSON files from many
CraftConnect sources, and he or she wants to merge the contacts from
these multiple files into one CraftConnect address book.

Let's allow the user to choose between data overwrite and data appending
whenever the user wants to import a JSON data file. The import command
will support an `--overwrite` flag, which tells the system to overwrite
existing contacts with new data from the JSON file. This also means that
by default, new data will be appended to the existing data, making it
more intuitive.

This also introduces another problem, that is new data conflicts with
existing contacts (such as a contact in existing contacts and another
contact in new data have the same unique identifiers. This is also a
problem for overwrite mode, where we cannot guarantee that a user's JSON
file contains unique contacts. The default behaviour when duplicated
contacts happen in overwrite mode is also just to display an error
message. However, suppose there are 1000 contacts in the JSON file, the
user will have to do a lot of checks before the new file contains only
unique data.

Let's allow the user to simply ignore subsequent duplicate contacts
(meaning that if there are multiple duplicate contacts, then only the
first contact is preserved). The import command will support another
flag `--ignore-duplicates`, which tells the system to simply not add
duplicated contacts into the address book instead of displaying a
duplicate contact error message. This also means that by default,
duplicated contacts will result in an erroe message.

Let's also modify StorageManager, AddressBookStorage,
JsonAddressBookStorage, JsonSerializableAddressBook to support another
method that reads a JSON file and ignore all duplicates, on top of the
pre-existing JSON-file-reading methods that will throw an error for
duplicated contacts. Extension of class is used instead of modifying
those read methods to accept another boolean attribute for ignore/not
ignore to not break the existing code base.
